<TEXT>
president turgut ozal of turkey said tuesday 
neighboring iraqs military strength has been exaggerated and he 
doesnt expect iraq to invade either saudi arabia or turkey 
iraqi president saddam hussein lost that chance to attack 
his neighbors with the arrival of us forces in saudi arabia ozal 
told a national press club luncheon 
recalling that it took iraqs army eight years to gain the upper 
hand in its war against iran despite backing from the soviet 
union france and most of the west ozal asked how can you call 
that iraq a strong army 
james dobbins deputy undersecretary of state for european and 
canadian affairs said ozal gave president bush a similar 
unflattering assessment of iraqi military prowess 
dobbins said ozal stated that public perception of saddams army 
being one of the strongest in the world was simply an exaggerated 
concern that youre not dealing with the kinds of crises the 
western world has dealt with in the past i dont think he was 
saying itll be a runover 
at the national press club ozal said neither he nor bush knew 
how long it would take for the economic embargo and other sanctions 
to force saddam to retreat his own view was maybe fourfive 
months maybe later well see 
asked if he took seriously saddams threats to attack oilfields 
in saudi arabia turkey and other neighboring countries resisting 
iraq ozal replied i never thought he was going to attack 
because i thought he was going to take kuwait and stop there if 
saddam had met no resistance he would stay in kuwait controlling 
the oil of both iraq and kuwait and probably have a tremendous 
effect on the rest of the gulf ozal said 
why should he attack saudi arabia why turkey he asked 
ozal dismissed as speculative a reporters suggestion that 
turkey wants to repossess oilrich mosul province from iraq after 
the gulf crisis although the ottoman empire considered it part of 
turkey the league of nations gave mosul to britishruled iraq 
after world war i and i think its all over he added 
</TEXT>
