<TEXT>
men firing submachine guns massacred 26 
laborers at a ranch in western colombia on tuesday an official in 
a nearby town said 
twentyfour workers were rounded up taken to a soccer field and 
shot as they huddled together an official in the town of 
candelaria said in a live broadcast interview with the radio chain 
rcn 
the town government spokesman jorge ramirez said in the 
interview with the radio chain rcn that two peasants on a road near 
the ranch were shot to death by the killers as they fled in three 
vehicles 
witnesses said the killers wore uniforms like those of 
colombias antinarcotics police rcn said 
both leftist guerrillas and rightwing death squads often 
disguise themselves in police uniforms a war between two drug 
cartels in colombia also has claimed more than 150 lives in the 
last two years 
there have been more than a dozen such massacres in the last 
three years in colombia investigations have shown that all were 
the work of rightwing death squads 
the federal attorney generals office has said that the death 
squads are run by drug traffickers who own immense ranches leftist 
guerrillas frequently try to extort money from ranchers 
the death squads kill people they suspect of being guerrillas or 
rebel sympathizers 
the reported massacre was at a ranch just outside candelaria 
about 225 miles west of the capital of bogota the town is in the 
state of valle 
policemen answering the telephone at the national police 
headquarters in bogota on tuesday night referred all questions 
about the reported massacre to the departments public affairs 
office 
the office as closed tuesday night when the associated press 
attempted to verify the report 
</TEXT>
