overall its been a pretty good year for dry 
edible beans says the agriculture department 
department bean counters always refer to them as dry and edible 
to distinguish the pintos navies and small reds from green beans 
which arent dry and castor beans which arent edible 
as of sept 1 total dry edible bean production is expected to 
be 314 million hundredweight the most since the record 1981 
harvest of 328 million hundredweight 
heat and drought conditions took a toll during the summer in the 
northern great plains or 1990 output would probably have exceeded 
the old peak 
even so prospects for this years bean harvest are much 
improved from 1989s harvest of 243 million hundredweight and the 
droughtriddled 1988 production of 193 million 
catherine r greene of the departments economic research 
service said recent industry reports show excellent growth 
conditions for much of the 1990 bean crop exceptions she said 
include drought areas of the northern plains and california 
greene said monday in a telephone interview that the aggregate 
prices of dry beans in the 199091 marketing year are expected to 
decline because of the larger harvest and a buildup in bean 
inventories 
in 198990 the season average price at the farm was about 28 
per hundredweight or 28 cents per pound during the summer farm 
prices rose to record levels averaging nearly 33 per 
hundredweight 
greene did not make any new price predictions but noted that her 
agencys most recent projection showed that bean prices might 
tumble to less than 20 per hundredweight over the 199091 season 
dry beans have been up for a long time she said 
according to usda analysts the harvested acreage jumped 26 
percent from last year to about 21 million acres with north 
dakota accounting for about half of the increase 
north dakota production which is mostly pinto and navy beans 
was indicated in september at 54 million hundredweight compared 
with 246 million in 1989 and 27 million in 1988 
another big dry bean producer is michigan with production 
estimated at 525 million hundredweight compared with 45 million 
last year and 214 million in 1988 
nebraska ranked third is expected to produce nearly 466 
million hundredweight up from less than 35 million in 1989 and 
376 million in 1988 
other commercial dry bean producers include california 
colorado idaho kansas minnesota montana new mexico new york 
oregon texas utah washington and wyoming 
 
washington ap an experimental oral vaccine to control 
coccidiosis a parasitic disease of chickens is being tested by 
the agriculture department 
so far says microbiologist mark c jenkins of the department 
agricultural research service the vaccine appears virtually 100 
percent effective in protecting young chickens against the 
disease 
jenkins who heads the research team at the agencys protozoan 
diseases laboratory in beltsville md said none of the 200 
chickens orally vaccinated became ill when exposed to the coccidial 
parasite 
the vaccine consists mainly of a preparation made from an 
ineffective stage of the parasite that has been bombarded with 
xrays making the organism sterile so it cant reproduce but it 
is still alive and can penetrate a chickens intestines 
our theory is that when the chickens are fed the sterilized 
coccidial parasite they react by producing antibodies and immune 
cells jenkins said in a report released monday this protects 
them from infection when exposed to diseasecausing parasites 
coccidiosis costs us poultry farmers more than 300 million a 
year in lost weight gain and medication he said most infected 
birds usually look healthy but the parasite prevents them from 
absorbing nutrients from the gut causing a sort of slow 
starvation 
scientists said the vaccine although promising is still a few 
years from practical use it will require at least another year of 
laboratory testing and then extensive field studies to make sure it 
is effective in large commercial flocks 
most poultry farmers now control coccidiosis by medicating the 
feed but the parasites often develop resistance to the drugs and 
new medications have to be developed 
 
washington ap us farm exports are expected to drop next 
year as foreign production competes with sales of grain and other 
products the agriculture department reports 
the departments economic research service said monday that a 
drop in corn exports in the fiscal year that begins oct 1 will 
help lead the overall decline 
us corn exports are expected to fall 7 million tons more 
than 275 million bushels as overseas customers replace us corn 
with competitors feed wheat the report said wheat prices are 
expected to average lower in 199091 due to larger crops but 
higher soybean prices will help offset some of this decline 
overall farm exports in the current year are estimated at about 
1485 million metric tons worth about 40 billion both up slightly 
from 198889 
the report did not include any figures to show us export 
values and volume in 199091 the departments first official 
export estimates for next year will be issued in late november 
