<TEXT>
hispanic leaders are overjoyed with president 
bushs pledge to improve federal efforts to promote quality 
education for hispanic americans 
bush flanked by education secretary lauro cavazos and interior 
secretary manuel lujan used a ceremony monday marking national 
hispanic heritage month sept 15oct 15 to issue an executive 
order on educational excellence for one of the fastest growing 
minorities in america 
stressing too many hispanic americans are not getting the 
firstrate education they need and deserve bush said the 
executive order sets up an advisory committee to keep the education 
secretary abreast of ways to improve federal educational efforts 
the order an outgrowth of an hispanic task force report also 
directs cabinet agencies to work along with individuals and 
educational business and community groups serving hispanic 
americans to increase participation rates of hispanics in federal 
education programs 
cavazos called the order a demonstration of bushs thorough 
commitment to bringing hispanics into the mainstream of american 
life through education 
the presidents intent in this policy is to improve education 
for all children who face obstacles in the education system he 
said 
lisa navarre spokeswoman for the national council of la raza 
said officials are encouraged by the order because the research and 
advocacy group along with the hispanic association of colleges and 
universities had been working for nearly two years to win a 
commitment from the administration 
on a political and general level this is a very significant 
and symbolic act said navarrete it shows an interest in the 
federal government to do something about the crisis in hispanic 
education 
antonio rigual president of the higher education group said 
we think that over the next six to 12 months we will see how the 
executive order translate itself into programs that begin to 
address the needs of hispanics 
our opinion has always been that our federal government has 
really turned its back on hispanic students but the order begins 
now to really position hispanic education institutions and 
hispanics in general to make special gains he said 
the nations hispanic population reached 201 million in march 
1989 a 39 percent increase over 1980 
the president noted that in five years hispanics will make up 
more than half the high school population in some major cities 
such as los angeles within 10 years he said 12 percent of all 
school children will be hispanic 
the national council of la raza said hispanics continue to have 
the highest school dropout rates of any major group about 43 
percent of hispanics age 19 or over have no high school diploma and 
are not enrolled in school 
we must find new strategies to boost graduation and literacy 
rates strategies that really do get the job done strategies that 
really work said bush 
we must figure out how to help these young people how to 
equip them with the tool to enter a nation in a world where 
technology advances so rapidly that literacy and analytical and 
technical skills are not luxuries but essentials 
in other federal initiatives the president said 
cavazos will work with governors from key states enrolling 
large number of students in migrant education programs to develop 
criteria for a high school diploma for migrant students 
federal education programs will intensify efforts to increase 
language development among preschool children head start will 
provide general guidance he said 
the education department will increase emphasis on early 
education programs under the bilingual education act to achieve 
english proficiency for preschool children lacking those skills 
the order acts upon recommendations from a special hispanic task 
force formed within the presidents domestic policy council with 
cavazos as the chairman the task force held public hearings on 
hispanic education in san antonio boston miami chicago and los 
angeles 
