lottery 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
the justice department is accusing the 
maryland lottery of bias against white men because it set aside 
several top positions for women and minorities in 1983 
the civil rights suit filed monday alleged that maryland and its 
lottery agency violated title vii of the 1964 civil rights act by 
refusing to hire qualified white males for the four positions set 
aside for minorities in 1983 
the lawsuit was denounced by a state official as an unwarranted 
attack on a onetime effort by maryland to recruit more minorities 
into the lottery agency 
two black men a black woman and a white women were recruited 
in response to a maryland human relations commission 
investigation and determination that the lottery agency was not 
doing enough to meet affirmative action requirements said dennis 
sweeney deputy state attorney general 
 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
people who regularly eat fish taken from 
streams near pulp and paper mills that discharge dioxin run a 
increased risk of developing cancer says the environmental 
protection agency 
the epa made public monday the results of a study showing that 
dioxin concentrations in fish downstream from 19 such mills may 
be high enough to pose an increased cancer risk greater than one in 
10000 to average consumers of fish caught there 
the estimated cancer risk is potentially higher for avid 
sports fishermen and subsistence level fishermen because their 
consumption of fish is generally higher than that of average 
consumers the epa said 
the epa said its risk estimates are based on the consumption of 
fish such as catfish bass suckers and squaw fish that spend 
their entire lives near a paper mill and accumulate greater 
concentrations of dioxin in their tissues 
the risk estimates do not apply to migratory fish such as 
salmon that spend only a short portion of their lives in the 
contaminated waters 
the onein10000 estimate is an upper bound any actual risk 
if present could be lower the agency generally tries to act 
against risks this large and treats smaller risks with less 
concern 
the average risk in the united states of dying of cancer from 
any source is about one in five 
 
 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
causing aids 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
federal health officials are collaborating 
with several hundred physicians in the united states and canada to 
gather more information about the progression of the infection that 
leads to aids 
the study will give medical researchers a better picture of 
which symptoms and diseases are most common in different groups of 
patients infected with the human immunodeficiency virus or hiv 
which causes aids officials said in announcing the study monday 
it also will provide information on what treatments patients are 
using and will help researchers identify medical changes that occur 
as hiv infection progresses towards acquired immune deficiency 
syndrome 
the study will allow researchers to compile a data base on a 
broad spectrum of hiv patients and will help physicians identify 
patients who can participate in clinical trials of experimental 
drugs officials said 
more than 30 communitybased clinics and programs in the united 
states and canada will participate in the study they include 18 
sponsored by the national institute of allergy and infectious 
diseases and 15 sponsored by the american foundation for aids 
research 
several hundred physicians will be able to enroll patients they 
see at these clinics and programs as well as patients they see in 
their private practices these physicians care for more than 60000 
hivinfected patients according to the research foundation 
