but the announcement apparently was a tactical maneuver to 
elicit support and his reelection appeared a victory for 
conservative forces 
lilov 57 became party leader in february four months after 
hardline leader todor zhivkov was ousted since then however 
bulgaria has made fewer changes in its communist system than some 
of its eastern european neighbors 
lilov had served as chief ideologist of the communist party 
until zhivkov dropped him from the leadership in 1983 he rejoined 
the top ranks only after zhivkovs ouster 
progressive and conservative factions of the renamed party are 
now vying for control throughout the congress spokesmen for 
reform factions repeatedly called for lilovs replacement 
but the reformers were outnumbered and their candidates stood 
no chance against lilov a socialist party official said monday 
that reformers numbered about onethird of the delegates 
in june the communists won bulgarias first free elections in 
58 years since then however their popularity has waned as the 
economy sputtered basic foods like sugar and cooking oil are 
rationed and electric power is cut regularly 
the socialists ended weeks of deadlock over bulgarias 
presidency by agreeing last month to elect zhelyu zhelev leader of 
the democratic opposition he serves as the countrys chief of 
state 
despite his election government opposition has sometimes turned 
violent an angry crowd of protesters attacked burned and looted 
the socialist party headquarters on aug 26 
that attack was reportedly provoked by the socialists refusal 
to remove a red star from its headquarters 
on monday the party congress voted to remove all such symbols 
of the communist era from party buildings and adopted a new emblem 
a white rose on a red background 
the congress decided monday that its new chairman would be 
chosen by the whole congress not just the partys supreme council 
of about 150 members it has also elected a new party presidium and 
council 
</TEXT>
