roach said he and eight other jurors thought the american 
tobacco co acted in an irresponsible way it was a very close 
decision we were fairly near a hung jury frankly 
the jury decided 93 monday that 35 years of smoking two packs 
of cigarettes a day had caused the 1987 lung cancer death of 
50yearold nathan henry horton 
the jurors half of them smokers heard 11 days of testimony 
about smoking risks and whether horton ran them by choice 
deliberations began monday and took about 5 hours 
the suit filed by horton and continued by his family named the 
american tobacco co and greenwood distributor new deal tobacco and 
candy co 
a first trial ended in a mistrial last year when jurors could 
not reach a verdict 
it was considered the most significant such case since a new 
jersey jury awarded a widower 400000 in 1988 after deciding a 
cigarette company was partly responsible for his wifes death from 
lung cancer in that case an appeals court this year overturned 
the award and ordered a new trial 
after mondays verdict horton family attorney don barrett of 
lexington asked circuit judge eugene bogen to award some sort of 
damages he also asked for a new trial on the issue of punitive 
damages 
bogen said he would rule later 
hortons widow ella mae horton of lexington refused to answer 
questions as she left the courtroom 
