president mikhail s gorbachev needed sweeping new 
powers to quickly carry out economic reforms not to introduce a 
state of siege his economic adviser said tuesday 
nikolai petrakov fended off charges that gorbachev was amassing 
too much power 
the supreme soviet parliament voted overwhelmingly monday to 
give gorbachev broad authority to order the switch to a market 
economy without consulting legislators every step of the way 
dissenting lawmakers said the special powers would make gorbachev a 
virtual monarch despite his vow to act responsibly 
the resolution permits gorbachev to issue presidential decrees 
for the next 18 months on property wages prices the national 
budget the financial system and law and order 
so why does the president need these extraordinary powers of 
course not for the purpose of introducing a state of siege or 
presidents rule petrakov told a news briefing 
some of the problems will have to be resolved in one two or 
three days and those decisions should be taken instantaneously 
he said it will be difficult to convene the parliament and 
discuss every issue 
the supreme soviet also voted in principle monday to end seven 
decades of inefficient centrally planned economics and take the 
leap toward a westernstyle free market lawmakers were unable 
however to decide which of three conflicting plans they liked 
best 
