<TEXT>
the chairman of a national bipartisan 
commission said tuesday that its 70 billion plan to guarantee 
universal access to health care is absolutely inevitable 
because of growing public anger over the current health system 
people who predict we cant do this are going to be wrong 
because the american people are going to make us do it said sen 
jay rockefeller dwva 
the panel headed by rockefeller and known as the pepper 
commission after its former chairman released the final report 
of its twoyear study while the basic elements of its proposal 
for overhauling medicaid and the health insurance system were 
decided last spring the panel provided supporting details and 
cited potential tax increases to pay its 70 billion price tag 
the recommendations drew criticism from opposite sides with 
some saying it was unrealistic and too expensive and others saying 
it fell short of a national health insurance solution 
the pepper commission report is a start but needs to be taken 
with a grain of salt said a republican member sen david 
durenberger of minnesota we didnt finish the job of building 
political consensus behind a solution but we did help define the 
problems and narrow the options and that sets the stage for the 
president to make his contribution 
the commissions recommendations were opposed by the bush 
administration which lobbied the commission members to oppose 
them rockefeller said 
the us bipartisan commission on comprehensive health care was 
established out of concern that more than 30 million americans have 
no health insurance and millions more face impoverishment by 
longterm care its first chairman was the late rep claude pepper 
dfla the longtime champion of americas senior citizens 
the commission plan calls for requiring all businesses with more 
than 100 employers to provide private health insurance or 
contribute to a new public plan for all employees and their 
dependents 
smaller employers would be given financial incentives to provide 
their employees coverage if after five years such coverage is 
not widespread those employers would be required to provide 
private insurance or participate in a new federal public health 
insurance plan 
the commission also would improve medicare coverage for the 
elderly and would establish a program to cover longterm care 
services including provisions for care within the home 
all would be guaranteed coverage for the first three months of a 
nursing home stay with extended benefits based on financial need 
people needing longterm care would not be required to spend 
themselves into poverty before receiving federal coverage as 
medicaid requires 
cost of the package was estimated at 24 billion for 
recommendations involving people under age 65 3 billion for 
elderly health care and 43 billion for longterm care when fully 
implemented after five years 
the commission said the 70 billion total amounts to 825 a 
week for every nonpoor adult in the country 
the plans face an uphill struggle in congress and bills to 
fully implement them wont even be ready until next year 
rockefeller is sponsoring with sen orrin hatch rutah a bill 
that would make a first step by extending medicaid to cover all 
lowincome children and pregnant women 
but with the administration and congressional leaders still 
debating ways to lower the budget deficit prospects for any action 
on expanding health care coverage are considered dim still 
rockefeller said the commissions plan or something like it will be 
enacted eventually 
it is absolutely inevitable rockefeller said before the 
end of this century well before the pepper commission or a plan 
similar to that will be the health care system of this country 
the commissions initial recommendations drew fire for failing 
to include recommendations for how to pay for it 
the commission made no financing recommendations but its final 
report includes six potential finance packages as possibilities 
key elements of include an increase in the top income tax rates a 
surcharge on all federal income taxes imposing a new valueadded 
tax and increasing social security taxes 
the report includes dissenting views from members including 
rep pete stark chairman of the house ways and means subcommittee 
on health he said a jobbased plan will not provide coverage to 
all americans and that the pepper commission failed to include 
realistic health cost containment proposals 
a single national plan is the only realistic way to make 
health insurance affordable to small employers said stark 
dcalif who has sponsored his own universal health care bill 
rep bill gradison rohio also on the commission pronounced 
the recommendations so costly that they are unrealistic 
