<TEXT>
the soviets stumbling transition to a free 
economy is unleashing a wave of economic crime and the black 
market is thriving on the sale of scarce goods senior police 
officials said tuesday 
investigators have found corruption at half of the 160000 
businesses they have inspected so far this year and cases of 
serious embezzlement are running at twice last years rate col 
vyacheslav i runyshkov of the ministry of internal affairs told a 
news conference 
the release of such alarming statistics on black marketeering 
indicated that law enforcement officials are concerned about social 
and economic problems stemming from the zigzag path to reform 
for a year the soviet government and legislature have been on 
the verge of moving from a planned to a market economy but have 
balked repeatedly throwing the system into chaos 
severe shortages of consumer goods such as bread and tobacco 
not only have caused widespread dissatisfaction but have fueled 
the already extensive black market 
the disappearance of goods between factories and stateowned 
retail outlets means the system will be able to provide only 32 
percent of the national requirements for medicine but purchases 
abroad could raise that figure to 68 percent said runyshkov who 
is in charge of the nations chief anticorruption unit 
he cited similar shortages of vegetables potatoes grain and 
other staples 
runyshkov strongly denied the shortages were caused either by a 
conspiracy among hardline communist party opponents of reform or 
by an organized crime network 
it is often said that this is a result of the actions of some 
destructive forces or the mafia he said i declare that 
neither the ministry of internal affairs nor the kgb have 
established this 
what is at hand is just negligence he said describing case 
after case in which workers diverted goods from state enterprises 
and sold them illegally 
asked to provide more specific reasons for the disappearance of 
bread or vegetables runyshkov and five other police officials 
laughed nervously and replied we dont understand it 
the phenomenon they described was one of many small and 
mediumsized thefts in which the goods turn up for sale in private 
shops called cooperatives or on the black market 
the chaos that has surrounded economic reform led the national 
legislature on monday to grant president mikhail s gorbachev broad 
powers to steer the country from a planned to a market system 
without consulting lawmakers every step of the way 
the resolution allows gorbachev to issue presidential decrees 
for the next 18 months on property wages prices the national 
budget the financial system and law and order 
the surge in economic crime indicates that the state 
distribution system appears to be disintegrating 
black market prices run two to three times those in state stores 
for most goods and three to five times for automobiles runyshkov 
said 
on sept 20 he said 650 stateowned butcher shops did not have 
meat 799 did not have sausage 1069 dairy shops had no eggs and 
1803 grocery stores had no sugar he did not cite the number of 
stores overall for comparison 
runyshkov said the number of people tried on major embezzlement 
charges doubled from last year to this year but he did not say 
specifically how many people were involved the number of people 
tried for economic crimes of all types was 188000 in the first 
eight months of this year he said 
