<TEXT>
alexander solzhenitsyns proposal to replace the 
soviet union with an allslavic state is destructive and 
disrespectful to the countrys other ethnic groups president 
mikhail s gorbachev said tuesday 
solzhenitsyn the nobel prizewinning author who was expelled 
from the soviet union for treason in 1974 made his proposal in an 
article published a week ago by two soviet newspapers 
in his first public comment on the article gorbachev told the 
national legislature that solzhenitsyn was an undoubtedly great 
man but his views on the future of our multinational state are 
unacceptable 
gorbachev cast himself as a politician dedicated to preserving 
the soviet union as a multiethnic country 
several lawmakers also attacked solzhenitsyn and none supported 
him or came to his defense 
solzhenitsyn believes russia has a unique heritage and destiny 
and he condemns soviet efforts to bind dozens of disparate cultures 
into a single nation 
solzhenitsyn 71 wrote his rambling philosophical article 
titled how we can make russia comfortable at his home in 
cavendish vt it was published sept 18 by the reformist newspaper 
komsomolskaya pravda and a day later by the literary weekly 
literaturnaya gazeta 
the newspapers have a combined circulation of 265 million and 
the article was an immediate sensation throughout the country 
discussed on moscow streets read by lawmakers and mentioned on the 
nightly tv news 
but until gorbachev was asked by a lawmaker to comment on the 
article tuesday there was no public reaction from a top government 
official 
the article which took up the equivalent of four full newspaper 
pages said communism had taken a flourishing country and turned it 
back into a halfsavage state 
but it also expressed disdain for western popmass culture 
and urged russia not to follow the west blindly 
solzhenitsyn urged a populist revival from below saying 
that russias villages and rural areas should be the starting point 
for the creation of democracy and a healthy economy 
he also advocated the breakup of collective farms called for 
free enterprise and warned against a political system in which 
parties compete for power every party tries to do its best not 
for the whole nation but for itself and its own members he 
wrote 
gorbachev focused on just one of solzhenitsyns many 
suggestions that russia byelorussia the ukraine and much of 
kazakhstan which are inhabited primarily by people of slavic 
extraction should form a single nation and let the other 11 soviet 
republics secede 
the article and the authors personality demand a very srious 
analysis gorbachev said i am seized by very contradictory 
feelings as a russian i fully share concern for the destiny 
of the russian people and russia 
but at the same time as a russian i definitely cannot agree 
with solzhenitsyns attitude toward other ethnic groups even by 
the most generous appraisal it is a disrespectful stand i cannot 
agree with it 
gorbachev added that solzhenitsyn was living entirely in the 
past the past russia the czarist monarchy 
the writers views are far from reality and have a 
destructive character he said 
gorbachevs remarks came as the national legislature began 
debate on how to negotiate a new union treaty with the 15 soviet 
republics gorbachev said he wants a union of sovereign states 
in which every ethnic group feels good and realizes its 
potential 
among the lawmakers who criticized solzhenitsyn was boris 
oleinik deputy chairman of the legislatures council of 
nationalities who said the writers views belittle the national 
dignity of many ethnic groups and could lead to separatism 
yurii shcherbak a lawmaker from the ukraine said 
solzhenitsyns proposals were underlined by messianic 
neomonarchist ideas of great power chauvinism 
the lawmaker who asked for gorbachevs comments was erkegali 
rakhmadiev of kazakhstan who objected to solzhenitsyns appeal for 
russians to take control of some kazakh lands he said in an 
interview later that the writers proposal was a hitlerite 
fascistic approach 
even delegates from republics that are seeking independence from 
the soviet union such as lithuania latvia estonia and georgia 
did not try to defend solzhenitsyn 
one bit of support for solzhenitsyn came tuesday from ryazan 
the city 100 miles southeast of moscow where solzhenitsyn wrote his 
books one day in the life of ivan denisovich and the cancer 
ward the city council officially gave him the freedom of 
ryazan an honor much like receiving the key to a city 
solzhenitsyns works describe life in soviet labor camps and 
were banned in the soviet union from the mid1960s until after 
gorbachev came to power in 1985 his books including the gulag 
archipelago are now being published but are still not widely 
available 
gorbachev restored the writers citizenship last month but 
solzhenitsyn has expressed reluctance about returning 
</TEXT>
