<TEXT>
syrian president hafez assad left tehran 
on tuesday after a fourday visit and sources said he failed to 
win a pledge from his iranian allies not to send food and other 
essentials to iraq 
sources close to the syrian delegation quoted assad as saying 
tehran did promise not to buy embargoed iraqi oil or to help 
baghdad export its crude through iranian pipelines 
iran has said it will enforce sanctions on neighboring iraq 
imposed by the united nations after saddam husseins aug 2 
invasion of kuwait 
the united states has formed a new alliance with syria since 
iraq invaded kuwait on aug 2 assad who met earlier this month in 
damascus with secretary of state james a baker iii is believed to 
have gone to tehran at washingtons behest to gauge the seriousness 
of irans suggestions it would send essentials to iraq 
but the sources speaking on condition of anonymity said 
washingtons main concern was whether the iranians intended to help 
iraq export oil its main source of revenue through their 
pipelines 
in his meetings with assad iranian president hashemi rafsanjani 
insisted that food supplies to iraq irans foe in the 198088 
persian gulf war did not violate those sanctions because 
humanitarian shipments are permitted the sources said 
assad has sent 4000 commandos to join the usled 
multinational force in saudi arabia and has pledged to send an 
armored division as well 
saddam internationally isolated and squeezed by the embargo 
suddenly made peace with iran last month ending two years of 
deadlocked peace talks 
the islamic republic news agency reported sunday that iranian 
authorities had arrested 29 smugglers trying to move foodstuffs 
across the border into iraq the first report of iran taking steps 
to enforce the sanctions 
the sources said assad carried a message to rafsanjani from 
saudi arabias king fahd calling for an improvement in the 
strained relations between the moslem rivals if tehran blocked 
supplies to iraq and sent troops to join the multinational force 
confronting saddam 
iran rejected the saudi conditions the sources said 
the saudi foreign minister prince saud alfaisal flew to 
damascus shortly before assad to get a firsthand account of the 
talks in tehran arab diplomats said 
rafsanjani leader of the countrys socalled pragmatists is 
eager to rebuild bridges with the west and is believed to favor 
abiding by the sanctions 
but he is under pressure from his powerful vehemently 
antiamerican radical rivals who want iran to help iraq confront 
the great satan 
the iranians have condemned the iraqi invasion but they have 
also criticized fahd for allowing nonmoseem western forces into 
saudi arabia where islams holiest shrines at mecca and medina are 
located 
riyadh severed ties with tehran in 1987 citing subversion and 
terrorism 
the sources reported that assad had some differences with 
iranian leaders but they said these were not so great as to drive 
a wedge between tehran and its arab ally 
before leaving tehran assad told a news conference that he and 
rafsanjani were in complete agreement on issues concerning the 
gulf tehran radio reported 
the broadcast monitored in nicosia quoted rafsanjani as 
confirming that on the gulf crisis our stance was completely in 
line with syrias 
assad was originally due to leave tehran on sunday but he 
extended his stay an extra day 
the sources said another item discussed in the meetings was the 
fate of 13 western hostages held by proiranian groups in lebanon 
where syria is the main power broker 
no results of the meetings were announced 
iranian diplomats said last week when assads visit was 
announced that some hostages could soon be freed 
most of the captives six americans four britons two west 
germans and an italian are held by shiite moslem factions linked 
to the fundamentalist hezbollah tehrans main ally in lebanon 
the longest held is terry anderson chief middle east 
correspondent of the associated press who was abducted march 16 
1985 
</TEXT>
