<TEXT>
bolivia on tuesday gave its indians 
control of vast tracts of troical rain forest and moved to limit 
exploitation by logging companies 
i have the feeling we are writing one of the most beautiful 
and clean pages in the contemporary history of bolivia president 
jaime paz zamora said monday night during a meeting with leaders of 
bolivias lowland indian community 
the measures were enacted after 800 indians from the lowland 
rain forests made a 35day march across the andes to the capital 
la paz to bring attention to the destruction of their environment 
the destruction of south americas tropical rain forests has 
become a major international concern because of the loss of 
irreplaceable species of plants and animals and because it may 
contribute to global warming 
under the new law 19 million acres of land in the beni 
tropical lowlands will be under the control of chimane indians 
two logging companies with operations in the area will be able 
to take wood from the forests only until dec 31 after that they 
will be allowed to bid for logging in new areas under 
governmentestablished ecological guidelines 
four other logging companies that have contracts for another 
year will be able to continue with operations the government says 
but once the contracts expire new concessions will not be granted 
on the lands whose control was ceded over the indians 
bolivias lumber companies and some other business leaders 
warned that limiting logging concessions would hurt foreign 
investment in the country 
logging companies mainly harvest mahogony trees most of the 
wood bound for the lucrative export market bolivia exported 40 
million worth of fine woods in 1989 the government says 
we are returning to our homes with dignity and with the 
knowledge that we have recovered our territories said indian 
leader ernesto noe we have managed to have doors opened to us 
and that our proposals be heard 
the group of indians including women and children marched 470 
miles from the city of trinidad to la paz which is 13000 feet 
above sea level 
at least 150000 indians live in the tropical rain forests 
northeast of la paz twothirds of bolivia is made up of tropical 
lowlands the indians are mainly nomadic hunters fishermen or work 
as hired hands at cattle ranches 
</TEXT>
