<TEXT>
nearly all usproduced foods and 96 percent 
of imported foods tested last year met government standards for 
pesticide residues the food and drug administration said tuesday 
in its annual study of pesticide residues the fda said most of 
the violations found during the regular testing involved pesticides 
being used on types of produce for which use of the chemicals is 
not allowed 
the violation rate in regular testing was about the same as for 
the three previous years for both domestic and imported foods the 
fda said 
however the violation rate in targeted testing of usproduced 
food where residue problems were known or suspected jumped from 25 
percent in 1988 to 33 percent last year 
still fda acting commissioner james benson said the report 
again demonstrates that the american food supply is the safest in 
the world and far freer from pesticide residues than many 
americans imagine 
but the us public interest research group called the fdas 
assessment an outrageous distortion rick hind environmental 
program director for the group said some of the sample sizes were 
too small to be meaningful 
for example he said the fda tested only 18 cranberries 
pesticide residues were found in 16 of them though the level in 
each was under the tolerance limit set by the environmental 
protection agency such a finding should have prompted more testing 
of that food type he said 
the report also shows that of the domestic samples 63 percent 
of apples 86 percent of grapefruit and 75 percent of celery had 
residues though within tolerance limits he said 
the federal government is presenting these numbers to prove 
the longheld political opinion that pesticide residues are not a 
problem he said 
hinds group also takes issue with the tolerance levels set by 
epa 
the fda tested 7394 samples of commonly consumed domestic foods 
and 10719 imports during regular surveillance monitoring in fiscal 
1989 
of these 1 percent of the domestic samples and 4 percent of 
imports violated pesticide residue limits the report said 
the agency also analyzed 304 domestic and 381 imported samples 
in compliance testing last year of these 33 percent of domestic 
and 16 percent of imports were in violation 
the agency tested for 270 pesticides and found 108 the report 
said this is about the same as found in previous years 
imported foods had higher levels of pesticide residues across 
most of the food groups according to the repor 
milk eggs and other dairy products were most often found to be 
free of residue the fda was unable to detect any residues in 90 
percent of the imports and 87 percent of the domestic samples in 
this category also none of the samples in this group was in 
violation of the tolerance limits 
fruits were more likely to contain residues the report said 56 
percent of the domestic samples and 60 percent of imports had no 
trace of pesticides while 43 percent of domestic and 38 percent of 
imported fruit samples had residues within the tolerance levels 
</TEXT>
