<TEXT>
imelda marcos testified with immunity tuesday 
before a federal grand jury investigating allegations that 
westinghouse electric corp bribed her late husband to secure a 
nuclear power plant contract 
the former first lady of the philippines who was greeted by 
cheering supporters as she entered and left the courthouse 
testified for more than two hours in the morning and returned in 
the afternoon 
the questioning was led by theodore greenberg deputy chief of 
the us justice departments fraud division 
mrs marcos attorney james p linn said she was questioned 
more about the jewelry on her hands than her knowledge of any 
illegal payoffs to her husband ferdinand the former philippine 
president 
thats not the purpose of the united states government linn 
told reporters before climbing into a limousine with mrs marcos 
and some of her entourage 
the grand jury subpoenaed mrs marcos in connection with 
allegations that pittsburghbased westinghouse paid 173 million 
in bribes to associates of marcos and to the former president who 
held office from 1965 until he was deposed in 1986 officials 
havent named the targets of the criminal probe 
the bribery allegations were made in a civil lawsuit philippine 
government filed in 1988 against westinghouse 
linn said mrs marcos knows nothing about any payments 
ferdinand marcos was not the kind of man who sat down every 
night and discussed business with his wife he said 
many in the crowd of about 100 filipinoamericans said they 
thought mrs marcos is being made a scapegoat by the us 
