<DOCNO> AP900925-0140 </DOCNO>
<TEXT>
federal investigators said tuesday that one of 
the worst commuter air crashes in us aviation history occurred 
last year when the pilot flew into a bank of clouds at a 
dangerously low altitude and slammed into a mountain ridge on 
hawaiis molokai island 
all 20 people aboard the aloha islandair plane were killed in 
the oct 28 1989 accident including eight members of the molokai 
high school volleyball team 
the national transportation safety board concluded that the 
probable cause of the accident was the decision of the pilot 
captain bruce pollard 30 to continue the flight into clouds that 
obscured the rising mountainous terrain 
but it also blamed the management of the commuter airline aloha 
islandair for inadequate supervision of its personnel and for 
inadequate training and operations 
and it said the federal aviation administration had failed to 
provide adequate supervision of aloha islandair operations 
particularly at a time when it was rapidly expanding its 
operations 
when youre operating carrying passengers there is an 
enormous responsibility there to the public said susan coughlin 
the safety boards vice chairman after the boards morninglong 
examination of the accident 
they were not taking the care that was necessary to assure 
safe flight and that is the responsibility of an air carrier 
she told reporters 
safety board members said that any one of a dozen factors could 
have resulted in preventing the aloha islandair accident plus two 
earlier ones in hawaii 
and they said it could have been avoided altogether had the 
plane been equipped with a ground proximity warning device 
the safety board said radar data revealed that the aircraft had 
descended from its intended cruising altitude of 1000 feet to 500 
feet when the crash occurred 
safety board staff members said flying at such a low altitude is 
prohibited by faa regulations and is basically illegal 
ms coughlin noted that investigators had discovered that aloha 
islandair had cut back required pilot training from the 44 hours 
ordered by the faa to 24 hours 
i would consider that a pretty important factor in this 
accident she said 
the board said pollard had a record of performance 
difficulties before joining alohaair including a 180day 
suspension 
and it faulted airline management for not adequately checking 
pollards background before hiring him 
it also said that the first officer on the flight had not 
received faaapproved ground training and was therefore 
disqualified to serve in that capacity 
</TEXT>
