<TEXT>
here are the environmental protection agencys 
fuel economy ratings for 1991 model cars vans and light trucks 
the first column gives the manufacturer and the model a d 
after the name indicates the vehicle has a diesel engine a g 
indicates the car is subject to the gas guzzler tax and a p 
indicates the car uses premium gasoline 
the second column shows miles per gallon in city driving the 
third column miles per gallon in highway driving and the fourth 
column miles per gallon combining both city and highway driving 
the fifth column indicates engine displacement in cubic inches 
and the number of cylinders 
the last column indicates the type of transmission and the 
number of gears an a designation indicates automatic 
transmission an l designation indicates automatic transmission 
with a fuelsaving device that eliminates slippage an m 
designation indicates manuel transmission for example an a4 
means a fourspeed automatic transmission an m5 means a 
fivespeed manuel transmission and an l3 means a threespeed 
automatic transmission with a fuelsaving antislippage device 
in some cases identical car listings with the same engine 
displacement cylinders and transmission may show slightly 
different mileage because of equipment or other differences not 
shown in the table 
the mileage figures reflect test conditions for some years the 
epa has adjusted the test results through the use of a weighting 
formula so the mileage more closely reflects actual driving 
conditions the combined mileage is calculated on an assumption 
that 55 percent of the miles driven are driven under city 
conditions 
the mileage tests are conducted by the manufacturer with about 
30 percent confirmed in separate tests by the epa some 
manufacturers may not have completed tests in time and their cars 
are not listed 
</TEXT>
<TEXT>
</TEXT>
</DOC>

