<TEXT>
harsher penalties should be levied against 
employers who discriminate against foreignlooking workers to avoid 
hiring illegal aliens an administration task force said tuesday 
the 1986 immigration reform and control act was not intended 
to be a barrier for persons who are eligible to work but the 
evidence shows that many employers are discriminating by adopting 
exclusionary hiring practices the task force said in its report 
to congress 
those practices include hiring only applicants who prove they 
were born on us soil and rejecting legal immigrants who present 
workauthorization documents issued by the immigration and 
naturalization service the study said 
attorney general dick thornburgh endorsed the work of the task 
force 
our nations continuing commitment to fighting discrimination 
in all its guises requires that there be sufficient penalties to 
deter discrimination and adequate enforcement of prohibitions 
against discrimination thornburgh said the task forces 
recommendations will further these goals 
the task force said fines for discriminating against 
foreignlooking workers should be commensurate with the penalties 
for employers who knowingly hire illegal aliens that would 
increase the maximum fine for repeated discrimination from 2000 
to 10000 it said 
the justice departments office of special counsel for 
immigrationrelated unfair employment practices should open three 
regional offices to investigate complaints and conduct programs to 
educate employers about their legal obligations the report said 
the special counsel now has one office in washington 
the task force also recommended streamlining the procedures for 
employers to check documents that applicants present to prove 
citizenship or legal status 
the interagency panel consisting of representatives of the 
justice department the equal employment opportunity commission and 
the civil rights commission adopted many of the findings of an 
earlier study by the general accounting office 
the 1986 immigration reform law provided amnesty for hundreds of 
thousands of illegal aliens living in the country when it was 
enacted 
</TEXT>
