<TEXT>
oleg yefremovs adaptation at the yale 
repertory theater of ivanov starring william hurt in the title 
role begins and ends with a gunshot 
but what happens in between is what really counts in this dark 
moody and unrealized production of one of anton chekhovs early and 
lesserknown plays 
ivanov has attracted attention not only because of hurt one 
of the few film stars willingly to put himself on stage with any 
degree of regularity but also because of yefremov artistic 
director of the moscow art theater 
the revival certainly looks authentic the design by david 
borovsky head artist of the moscow taganka theater is a marvel of 
the power of suggestion the decrepit facade of a country mansion 
its columns covered with gnarled leafless vines fills the wide 
playing area at the university theater 
with a few chairs strategically placed on stage in front of this 
haunted house the director conjures up the deadening bourgeois 
activity of two different families in vastly different financial 
situations 
yefremov is not afraid to tamper with the text for example he 
reshuffles scenes opening the play with a secondact party that 
has the guests commenting on ivanovs tribulations before the 
audience has seen him 
and the title character has enough troubles for several dramas 
ivanov is a man in despair i dont believe anymore he says 
he doesnt believe in his marriage to sarah his rich jewish wife 
whose parents cut off love and money to her after she married and 
he spends more time worrying about his debts than trying to earn 
money to pay them off 
but an articulation of his anxiety is hard to find in hurts 
muffled portrait of ivanov the blond bearded hurt can be a 
galvanizing actor on stage as audiences who saw his jumpstart 
performance off and on broadway in david rabes hurlyburly 
know 
here his acting is muted his voice rarely rising above a drone 
whatever magic yefremov has worked on the plays atmosphere has not 
filtered down to his star 
other members of the large underrehearsed cast seem to be left 
to their own resources losing both the comedy and the tragedy of 
the piece some fare better than others frances conroy as the 
dying sarah conveys the evenings only real sense of sadness 
zeljko ivanek has mastered the outrage of a young doctor amazed at 
ivanovs treatment of his critically ill wife and lee richardson 
has the right amount of charm as ivanovs reprobate uncle 
but austin pendleton and susan kellermann flounder as ivanovs 
prosperous neighbors and leo burmester is more allamerican 
farmhand than savvy country bumpkin 
the result is an incomplete production tantalizing for the 
atmosphere yefremov is able to coax from a production team that 
also includes costume designer jess goldstein and lighting designer 
geoff korf 
this ivanov which runs in new haven through oct 13 is an 
inviting shell of a play but not a world inhabited by real people 
</TEXT>
