<TEXT>
a federal judge tuesday threw out 
campaign contribution limits imposed by california voters in 1988 
saying they give an unfair advantage to incumbents 
us district judge lawrence karlton knocked out the limits 
created by proposition 73 and also tossed out the propositions ban 
on transfers of funds between candidates 
the ruling sent a shock wave through californias political 
establishment although it was uncertain what effect the ruling 
would have on the gubernatorial race between democrat dianne 
feinstein and republican pete wilson 
both national political parties concerned over the outcome of 
the governors race because of reapportionment stemming from the 
1990 census have targeted the california governors race as a top 
priority 
if allowed to stand the decision means candidates for governor 
other statewide posts and in some cases local offices will have 
no contribution limits during the remaining six weeks of the 
election campaign a spokeswoman for the fair political practices 
commission said 
but fppc chairman john larson warned candidates not to start a 
fundraising frenzy saying the commission would ask karlton to 
stay his rling proposition sponsors also said they would appeal 
the decision 
larson said that if the decision remains in place the fppc will 
enforce similar contribution limits in proposition 68 but that 
measure applies only to legislative candidates 
voters approved both propositions 68 and 73 in june 1988 but 73 
took effect because it got more votes however a few minor 
provisions of 68 also became law 
proposition 73s limits which among other things allow 
individuals to give no more than 1000 to a particular candidate 
per fiscal year apply to state and local candidates 
the measure also allows political action committees to give up 
to 2500 or 5000 per candidate per fiscal year depending on the 
size of the committee 
assembly minority leader ross johnson and state sen quentin 
kopp isan francisco two of the coauthors of proposition 73 
said they planned to ask the 9th circuit court of appeal on 
wednesday to overturn karltons ruling 
the timing of this decision is most unfortunate johnson 
said closing arguments were heard april 19 and we finally get a 
ruling just six weeks before election day there will be enormous 
confusion now as hundreds of candidates at all levels of government 
try to figure out what the new rules are 
proposition 73 was sponsored as an alternative to the 
reformgroupsupported proposition 68 and bases its contribution 
limits on fiscal years that start on july 1 
since state election campaigns typically span two calendar 
years the measure creates three contribution periods the first 
six months of the nonelection year the last six months of the 
nonelection year and the first half of the election year and the 
last half of the election year 
that means that an individual contributor can give a candidate 
3000 over two calendar years 
critics say the fiscalyear format helps incumbents because they 
usually start raising funds earlier than challengers karlton 
agreed 
karlton issued the decision in response to a lawsuit filed by 
the state democratic party and labor unions which said proposition 
73 unfairly limited constitutional rights to free speech and 
association 
</TEXT>
</DOC>

