<TEXT>
in a decision that could have a 
profound impact on the november governors election a federal 
judge tuesday threw out campaign contribution limits imposed by 
california voters in 1988 
the decision if allowed to stand means candidates for 
governor other statewide posts and in some cases local offices 
will have no contribution limits during the remaining six weeks of 
the campaign said a spokeswoman for the state fair political 
practices commission 
us district judge lawrence karlton said the limits give an 
unfair advantage to incumbents karlton also tossed out the a ban 
on transfers of funds between candidates that was imposed by the 
same ballot initiative 
the ruling invalidated proposition 73 which among other 
things limits individuals to a maximum of 1000 in contributions 
to a particular candidate per fiscal year the measure also limits 
political action committees donations of 2500 or 5000 per 
candidate per fiscal year depending on the size of the committee 
the ruling sent a shock wave through californias political 
establishment although it was uncertain what effect the ruling 
would have on the gubernatorial race between democrat dianne 
feinstein and republican pete wilson 
wilson who had only token opposition in the june primary 
raised 125 million through june and had 39 million in the bank 
as of july 1 feinstein raised 81 million through june but had 
only 645344 left over from her primary campaign against state 
attorney general john van de kamp 
aides to both candidates claimed not to know how much they have 
raised since june 
