what to do 
she said that removal of the limits gives us a chance to close 
the gap a little but she predicted wilson would still raise more 
money 
but john larson chairman of the fair politicial practices 
commissio warned candidates against a fundraising frenzy 
saying the commission would ask karlton to stay his ruling the 
proposition sponsors also said they would appeal the decision 
the decision was in a lawsuit filed by the state democratic 
party and labor unions which said proposition 73 unfairly limited 
constitutional rights to free speech and association 
proposition 73 which was sponsored by three legislators as an 
alternative to the reformgroupsupported proposition 68 bases its 
contribution limits on fiscal years that start on july 1 
since state election campaigns typically span two calendar 
years the measure creates three contribution periods that means 
that means an individual contributor can give a candidate 3000 
over two calendar years 
in this election for example a candidate who began 
fundraising early could collect up to the limit from a particular 
contributor for the period from january through june of 1989 then 
the same person could again donate the limit for the fiscal year 
that ran from july 1989 through june 1990 and he could give again 
before the election in the fiscal year that began july 1 
critics say the fiscalyear format helps incumbents because they 
usually start raising funds earlier than challengers karlton 
agreed 
voters approved both propositions 68 and 73 in june 1988 but 73 
took effect because it got more votes however a few minor 
provisions of 68 also became law where they didnt conflict with 
prop 73 
