<TEXT>
an israeli soldier stares through binoculars to 
penetrate the privacy of a palestinian home he sees laundry 
billowing in the breeze falls secretly in love with a young 
palestinian woman and witnesses a tragic explosion 
in the scenes from the new movie lookout the soldier is 
largely passive director dina zvi riklis says her intent was to 
shake israelis out of their complacency about the 31month 
palestinian uprising 
the film the latest in a series of israeli movies on the 
palestinian conflict won the golden dove award as the best short 
film at this summers jerusalem film festival 
it starts with an anonymous soldier in a lookout post above a 
neighborhood in the occupied gaza strip he twists a radios dial 
to the station whose hebrew news and chatter along with american 
and israeli rock music will be almost the only sound for the 
films 28 minutes 
riklis camera shows the life of a palestinian family through 
the eyes of the brownhaired reservist in his late 20s 
he sees a palestinian father builds a pigeon coop atop his roof 
and his son sets free the birds on the street two soldiers 
confiscate a soccer ball from palestinian boys 
as the soldier looks down on the dusty streets in gaza the 
radio deejay brightly announces a day on the mediterranean we 
love the weather here 
the soldiers glance is drawn across the street to an old arab 
house built of stones with arched windows a 7yearold boy lives 
there and his teenage sister innocent and stunningly beautiful 
the girl knows she is being watched and seductively lingers near 
her window in his only descent from the lookout post the soldier 
walks by the house and encounters the girl they stare into each 
others eyes but do not speak 
when the girl marries a palestinian activist she changes her 
dark lush hair is covered by a scarf in moslem fashion the 
husband closes the bedroom window shutters blocking the soldiers 
view 
in the living room the family watches a television news report 
showing troops savagely beating arabs a youth unfurls a 
palestinian flag 
the soldiers sees the familys life but his only line in the 
movie i didnt see anything comes as troops raid the house 
and arrest the womans father 
in the gripping climax the womans husband sends her brother to 
deliver a package to the father as he returns from a military 
lockup an army patrol appears and the boy hurriedly tosses aside 
the package it explodes the boy dies before his fathers eyes 
now the lookouts passivity ends he stares at the boys limp 
body raises his rifle and kills the young husband 
in an eerie epilogue the palestinian woman paces her porch 
months later singing to her newborn child still watched by a 
lookout but the reservist is gone a different wideeyed soldier 
gazes on 
for israelis riklis film presents the unfamiliar world of 
palestinians in the gaza strip juxtaposed with the familiar chatter 
of an israeli radio show 
radio is almost the second voice of the nation it is still 
not a medium of entertainment here but taken very seriously 
said deejay dori benzeev whose show was on the soundtrack 
what the soldier sees is a story riklis said what he 
hears on the radio is reality i wanted to take a difficult 
situation and hit the audience with our indifference the events 
in the territories are the same only we get used to hearing them 
and they dont phase us anymore 
the film is more a mix of documentary with drama than two recent 
israeli films that focus on relations with palestinians 
green fields winner of the featurefilm award at the 1989 
jerusalem festival follows an israeli family on a destructive 
journey in the west bank one of ours israels entry in this 
years academy awards is about the slaying of a palestinian 
prisoner 
