<TEXT>
it was 1130 am when rude laughter and the 
whoosh of rushingwater sundered deborah terrells algebra lesson 
the odds against the lesson already were high enough for ms 
terrell and her 19 eighthgraders at burnet street elementary 
school a magnet school where 200 of 500 children are homeless 
this day like most ms terrell has spent here for the last 
decade would be a melange of frustration fatigue selfdoubt and 
perhaps a small victory or two 
but as she spoke of equations a former student in a prankish 
mood gleefully sprayed the glass in her classroom door with jets 
from the hallway fire extinguishers 
see that she said pointing angrily to the truant this 
is fun what kind of life is that 
later that day as if sent to restore her faith a second 
visitor dropped in tawana woolridge a prim polite 12thgrader at 
newarks tough central high whom ms terrell had taught five years 
earlier 
she was my favorite teacher tawana said she wasnt too 
strict but she didnt let you get away with anything either 
when one kid like that comes back and is making it thats 
what makes it all worthwhile said the teacher 
 
3 pm at last 
most of the students leaving room 303 headed for baxter terrace 
or other downtown newark housing projects three caught buses for 
homeless shelters at the lincoln or carlton hotels 
ms terrell slumped back in her chair exhausted 
she hadnt always wanted to be a teacher she studied psychology 
at rutgers university but quickly lost her taste for it after an 
internship at a mental health center too depressing 
when i went to school everyone wanted to be a teacher i came 
here to burnet to do my student teaching the seventhgrade teacher 
left one day and the principal just gave me her class the rest is 
history 
at age 36 her chosen career now earns her about 33000 a year 
i dont see myself here for another 10 years but i guess i 
wonder if i leave whos going to be here for these kids 
later back home in her neat woodframe house on a 
toughlooking downtown newark street shed make sure her sons 
malcolm 8 and toussaint 9 buckled down to homework as her own 
mother once had for her 
but now as the last pupil straggled out she needed to 
decompress 
i have to wind down before i can see my kids she said if 
i dont take half an hour to wind down i might take things out on 
them 
after dinner homework awaited grading neatly bound projects 
her students had prepared on the evils of drugs to mark national 
drug awareness month then she planned to phone parents to exhort 
them to attend open school night 
she wondered aloud am i just speaking to the air did anyone 
learn anything today 
she thought 
well i know murad learned something 
murad a bright cocky reedthin boy is quick with excuses and 
short on study habits ms terrell had forced him to sit in a desk 
alongside hers a spot known in her class as out of society 
but today murad actually had taken notes in class and used them 
to solve a math problem 
a small victory 
and ronald a big day for him too quiet withdrawn homeless 
for the last year ronald had stood up for the first time and given 
an oral presentation the class had applauded ronald had smiled 
shyly 
another victory 
victories come hard at burnet street designated four years ago 
a magnet school for homeless children in kindergarten through 
eighthgrade only last year did the board of education add staff 
and resources to help the school accommodate this most troubled 
population teachers say they have yet to get any formal training 
on how to deal with them 
kids wre sleeping on desks had to meet bus schedules had to 
make stops at the grocery stores ms terrell said 
average daily attendance at burnet street is just 876 percent 
the national average is more than 92 percent twenty percent at 
burnet need special help with basic skills and 15 percent have 
been held back a grade or more only 5 percent of parents 
participate in school activities according to new jersey state 
statistics 
for ms terrell teaching is a daily gantlet of delays 
interruptions excuses 
the pa system squawks messages the bell rings every 45 minutes 
in the space of a morning the attendance teacher knocks on the 
door to take roll four hispanic students get pulled out of class 
for special english classes eight others are summoned for remedial 
classes to boost low english and math test scores still another 
group goes for computer instruction in the afternoon ms 
terrells homeless students are called away early to catch buses to 
shelters 
and then there are the excuses 
a kid tells her she didnt do her homework because i left the 
book in school ok 
at that ms terrells mouth twists upward in a streetwise curl 
that says without words you think i havent heard that nonsense a 
thousand times before you think youre kidding me i was raised in 
the same streets you were 
no she finally says thats not ok you know how i feel 
about excuses and thats not even a good one and get rid of the 
gum 
she has a way of mixing humor affection and discipline on her 
desk is a small sign u toucha my desk i breaka u face 
sometimes shell say with a hint of a smile you know how 
unrational i am 
how do the kids feel about her 
defiant yet dependent she sometimes invites her students to 
write what they think without signing their papers they write her 
things they wouldnt tell their parents about drugs aids their 
neighborhoods being homeless 
 
her kids say ms terrell sometimes gets teary during her life 
lectures when she speaks about what she wants for them why 
shes there 
one such talk comes minutes after the classs standardized state 
test scores arrive 
the 7th grade scores the ones her kids took the spring before 
show only 28 percent testing above average in math the lowest 
passing rate in the school by far 
oh brother she says were the lowest on the list 
everyone has so much time to talk and play talk and play 
what bothers me is i know you can do better these scores are 
garbage thats a reflection on me whatever i have to do to get 
this up i will do 
you always should expect to do the best for yourself theres 
too much potential in this room im just here to help you but you 
have to help me help you you already have the strikes against you 
youre minorities blacks puerto ricans so people look at these 
scores and say what did you expect 
i know where you belong and i want to take you i certainly 
dont want any of you in here next year shooting fire extinguishers 
at the window 
