<TEXT>
a judge has ordered the release of 
presentencing documents about michael milken which could provide 
revealing information about the convicted financier before his 
punishment is officially announced 
but the ruling monday by us district judge kimba wood said the 
released documents would be edited to delete possibly incriminating 
information about others 
she also left unclear whether milkens sentencing would proceed 
as scheduled oct 1 less than a week away 
her ruling was part of lastminute legal maneuvers surrounding 
the sentencing of milken the biggest and richest figure to fall in 
a federal crusade against securities fraud crimes that began in the 
late 1980s 
milken reversed claims of innocence in april pleaded guilty to 
six felonies and paid a record 600 million in fines and penalties 
to settle the biggest securities fraud case ever against a single 
person 
in the past few weeks prosecutors and defense attorneys have 
given wood exhaustive documents to guide her in determining a 
sentence for milken who faces a possible 28 years in prison 
news organizations sought copies of the documents before the 
sentencing date but milkens lawyers opposed an early release on 
grounds it could unfairly prejudice the sentencing 
i reject that contention theres no jury here wood told a 
hearing at manhatttan federal court delaying the release of the 
information she said may prejudice the ability of the press to 
understand it 
she ordered prosecutors to release edited versions of their 
sentencing memos that avoid references to other individuals or 
pending criminal investigations they were expected to be available 
later today 
defense lawyers declined to comment on woods ruling but said 
they would release similarly edited versions of their sentencing 
memos at about the same time 
although the documents are edited people familiar with the case 
said monday they could provide revealing insights into the scope of 
governments enormous case against milken as well as the depth of 
his defense 
milken is widely perceived as one of the most influential 
financiers in the 1980s who made a fortune by parlaying highrisk 
securities known as junk bonds into a 200 billion market 
although milken pleaded guilty to only six crimes related to 
securites and tax crimes prosecutors have been seeking to persuade 
the judge to consider a list of other illegal acts they say milken 
committed 
they have asked for an extraordinary hearing on this question 
which could delay milkens sentencing wood did not say whether she 
would grant such a hearing but asked assistant us attorney john 
carroll to provide examples of other cases in which similar 
hearings were requested 
the case against milken is by far the most important result of 
an intensive federal crackdown on securities fraud that surfaced 
nearly four years ago when stock speculator ivan boesky paid the 
government 100 million to settle charges of trading on inside 
information 
boeskys revelations led to numerous prosecutions and played a 
role in the downfall of milkens former employer drexel burnham 
lambert inc the oncefeared wall street powerhouse that is now 
out of business 
milken pioneered drexels use of junkbond financing for 
takeover deals and he had extensive and close links with a number 
of leading american investors and speculators 
