against neil bush opened today with a judge rejecting a witness 
attempt to invoke the fifth amendment and offering to take 
testimony in private a second witness refused to talk voluntarily 
and faced a subpoena 
the federal office of thrift supervision is trying to bar the 
presidents son from the banking and savings industry the 
regulators in february accused neil bush of wrongdoing in his 
former role as a director of silverado banking savings and loan 
which failed in late 1988 at an cost to taxpayers of 1 billion he 
could be banned from the banking and savings industry 
the presidents 35yearold son a denver oil and gas developer 
was not present when the hearing began today before a nearly full 
courtroom bush who adamantly denies wrongdoing was expected to 
be the final witness of 11 scheduled to testify this week 
after the hearing was called to order today former silverado 
chairman michael wise asserted his fifth amendment right to refuse 
to answer questions on the ground that he could incriminate 
himself 
administrative law judge daniel j davidson disagreed that the 
right could be claimed at such a hearing saying i do have the 
authority to require mr wise to answer despite his claim to the 
fifth amendment 
he then adjoured the opened hearing and the participants went 
into a closed session in his chambers 
it was not immediately clear whether wise agreed to testify in 
private or continued to take the fifth wise left the closed 
hearing after about a halfhour and would not respond to reporters 
questions 
davidson had said that wises testimony in his chambers would be 
on the record and that a transcript would be made available later 
probably at the end of todays hearing 
another former silverado director scheduled to testify florian 
barth today gave a letter to ots lawyers saying he will not 
testify voluntarily davidson promptly announced he would sign a 
subpoena aimed at forcing barths testimony 
the open hearing finally got under way with former silverado 
executive vice president russell m murray he answered questions 
put by bushs attorney james nesland who attempted to show that 
murray was aware that silverado had guidelines for approving loans 
and lines of credit to board members 
the ots is seeking an order against bush banning him from the 
industry to avoid alleged conflicts of interest the president has 
said he will not interfere with the disciplinary process 
last week bush and other former silverado directors were also 
sued for 200 million by the federal deposit insurance corp the 
lawsuit alleged that gross negligence on the part of silverado 
directors contributed to the sampls collapse 
ots contends bush failed to disclose adequately to silverado his 
business relationships with kenneth m good and bill l walters 
two big borrowers from silverado who defaulted on loans totaling 
more than 130 million 
the two denver developers helped finance bushs oil and gas 
company jnb exploration at the same time bush voted on the mens 
requests from silverado for millions in loans and a line of credit 
the ots has alleged 
bush could have avoided the hearing by agreeing not to dispute 
the charges as other sampl officials have done by fighting the 
government he has taken the case out of attorneys and regulators 
offices into a rare public forum 
the swords are drawn his attorney james nesland said 
recently 
the judge has until dec 6 to recommend a ruling to ots director 
timothy ryan who has until april 8 to make a final decision on 
whether to impose the sanctions bush could appeal most likely to 
a federal appeals court in denver 
in his testimony today murray discussed a 900000 line of 
credit that bush and denver developer kenneth good obtained from 
the silverado board in 1986 for an oil and gas exploration 
partnership in argentina 
the line of credit never was tapped but the boards approval of 
the request is one of the conflictofinterest counts leveled by 
the ots against bush who voted as a board member on the 
transaction 
murray said he talked to good bush and wise about the line of 
credit and decided to submit the matter to the silverado investment 
committee and then to the silverado board because of bushs 
involvement in the deal 
i knew there were some limitations on loans to officers and 
directors murray said 
