<TEXT>
multimillionaire financier sir jack lyons was 
fined 3 million pounds or 56 million tuesday for his part in 
the guinness takeover scandal but escaped a jail sentence because 
of ill health 
the judge also announced that guinness chairman ernest saunders 
sentenced to five years in the same case would not have to face a 
second trial on related charges because the prosecution had decided 
it would not be in the public interest 
at southwark crown court judge sir denis henry said lyons was 
guilty of dishonesty on a major scale and could have expected a 
threeyear prison sentence 
but after medical testimony that lyons 74 had cancer heart 
problems high blood pressure and chronic bronchitis the judge 
said he would not send lyons to jail 
lyons was ordered to pay 440000 pounds 831000 toward 
government legal costs 
lyons was convicted aug 27 on six counts of conspiracy to 
commit fraud false accounting and theft 
he and three other figures in londons city financial district 
were charged with organizing an illegal operation to boost the 
stock market price of shares in guinness during a successful 
takeover battle for distillers co a scotch whisky and gin maker 
the distillers takeover involved buying large blocks of guinness 
shares to make them more attractive than those of rival bidder 
argyll a supermarket operator 
the prosecution claimed guinness paid about 25 million pounds 
48 million at the time in unlawful indemnities against losses in 
share dealing and in fees for a successful outcome 
lyons bought guinness shares for himself and clients and was 
paid more than 3 million pounds 58 million in illegal success 
fees and indemnities he later repaid nearly 2 million pounds 
nearly 4 million of the money he received 
the other three tried with lyons were sentenced earlier 
saunders 55 chairman and chief executive of the guinness brewing 
giant received five years 
stockbroker anthony parnes 45 was sentenced to 2 years while 
gerald ronson 50 received one year and a record fine of 5 million 
pounds 975 million 
