<TEXT>
michael milkens lawyer has asked the judge who 
will sentence him for fraud to spare the former junkbond king from 
imprisonment and let him repent by helping innercity youth court 
papers released today said 
such a sentence would constitute a most serious punishment 
but it would be purposeful punishment wrote his lead attorney 
arthur liman in a sentencing proposal to us district judge kimba 
wood 
he said milken could work under the auspices of the los angeles 
police department near the financiers home and that its chief 
daryl f gates supported the idea it would not only embody the 
concept of social restitution but would also hold him fully 
accountable and punish him for his behavior in the most appropriate 
way liman said 
the lawyer also asserted that milken 44 already has been 
punished severely by nearly four years of intense public scrutiny 
payment of a record 600 million in fines and penalties and a bleak 
future fighting civil lawsuits 
we cannot adequately describe the anguish and devastation that 
this experience has caused michael an intensely private and 
sensitive individual the memorandum said everyone who has 
come into contact with him speaks of his acute pain and 
suffering 
limans sentencing proposal portrayed milken as a brilliant 
selfless family man who spurned the life of the rich and famous 
despite amassing enormous wealth in the securities industry over 
nearly two decades 
michaels passion lies in his ideas his life has been devoted 
to seeking value for others for michael substantial 
compensation was a byproduct of his ideas the defense said 
the proposal was hundreds of pages long and was accompanied by 
lengthy appendices with statements of support from more than 240 
people ranging from close relatives and leading business figures to 
milkens family rabbi 
milkens lawyer released the sentencing proposal to wood with 
less than a week to go before she is scheduled to pronounce 
punishment for milken the most influential financier of the 1980s 
and the biggest figure to fall in the wall street securities fraud 
scandal that broke in 1986 
such sentencing proposals are usually released on the day a 
defendant is sentenced but because of the enormous interest in the 
milken case wood ordered versions released early edited to delete 
incriminating references to others the government was working to 
make its version available later 
milken former head bond trader at the once powerful drexel 
burnham lambert inc reversed longstanding claims of innocence and 
pleaded guilty to six felonies in april most of the charges were 
linked to his relationship with fallen stock speculator ivan f 
boesky 
there has been intense speculation about what sentence will be 
imposed by wood who has been swamped with letters both in support 
of leniency and heavy punishment he faces a maximum of 28 years in 
prison 
wood has given no indication what she will do but the 
government has urged her to consider a vast array of unproven 
crimes milken allegedly committed 
in its reply to the prosecutions sentencing memorandum the 
defense argued that the judge should not consider any evidence 
relating to other alleged crimes it also asked the court not to 
punish the financier for the collapse of drexel or in reaction to 
his considerable wealth 
the defense said the governments strategy of presenting 
additional allegations prior to sentencing violated milkens 
constitutional rights 
it also said that imposing a provisional sentence subject to 
possible reduction based on the value of milkens cooperation with 
the governments continuing investigation of insider trading 
would violate both his constutional rights and his earlier plea 
agreement 
