<TEXT>
the senate decided against cutting off debate 
today on legislation requiring more fuelefficient cars a major 
setback for a bill automakers claim would require them to stop 
making large cars 
the senate rejected 5742 a petition asking that the measure be 
brought to a vote sixty votes were needed to cut off debate 
the bill would require cars to achieve a fleet average of 35 mpg 
by 1995 and 40 mpg by 2001 the bills sponsor sen richard bryan 
dnev said that eventually would save 28 million barrels of oil 
a day 
bryan had said he was optimistic about the legislations passage 
and argued the higher automobile fuel efficiency requirements were 
needed to curb americas thirst for foreign oil 
but opponents led by sen donald riegle dmich waged an 
intense campaign against the measure maintaining that the tougher 
fuel economy requirements would lead to the production of smaller 
cars and increased traffic deaths 
the automakers in recent week lobbied intensely against the 
legislation and auto industry unions sent thousands of telegrams to 
senators urging the legislation not be approved 
the measures chances all along appeared brightest in the 
senate 
even some supporters expressed doubt that the bill would be 
approved in the house where it is staunchly opposed by rep john 
dingell dmich chairman of the energy and commerce committee 
through which the bill normally must be channeled 
aides to president bush have said they would recommend a veto if 
the bill is approved by congress 
late monday the senate rejected 4946 an amendment by sen paul 
simon dill that would have provided special unemployment aid 
for workers who lose their jobs because automakers must shift to 
producing more fuelefficient vehicles 
sen slade gorton rwash a bill cosponsor said the simon 
amendment would doom this bill because of many senators 
opposition to a worker assistance proposal 
meanwhile an amendment was approved 5540 to include new 
incentives for automakers to produce vehicles that can run on 
alternative fuels such as methanol ethanol or compressed natural 
gas the measure would let manufacturers claim more credits against 
fuel efficiency requirements if they produce such vehicles 
the floor debate monday centered on whether the high fuel 
economy requirements would force manufacturers to dramatically 
reduce the size of their cars and doom the future of the 
sixpassenger family sedan 
it means smaller cars it means less safe cars declared 
riegle whose state is home to the major us automakers 
bryan disputed such claims arguing that higher fuel efficiency 
can be achieved without sacrificing car size he noted that auto 
executives made the same claims in the 1970s when faced with 
tougher fuel economy requirements 
that just didnt happen the sixpassenger vehicle is here 
just as it was before said bryan 
