<TEXT>
from the boxing ring to the trading ring ray 
pace never has been one to back down 
but in a federal courtroom that is the venue for his latest 
confrontation pace fights the feeling that he is already whipped 
he says its not because he has no hope of winning his case but 
because the cost of his defense has nearly wiped him out 
to see that everything youve saved is gone because of this 
trial its a hard pill to swallow said pace an amateur boxer 
in the chicago area from 1976 to 1981 
pace 34 is one of 14 commodity traders from the chicago 
mercantile exchange standing trial on charges of defrauding 
customers while executing their orders in the mercs busy japanese 
yen futures pit 
he also is accused of racketeering conspiracy a charge that 
carries a maxmimum penalty of 20 years in prison and possible 
confiscation by authorities of his home and personal property 
pace is not a poor man for several years before his indictment 
in august 1989 he could gross more than 1000 in commissions on a 
good day working as a broker in the yen pit 
but neither is he one of the relatively few millionaire 
speculators personifying the popular perception of chicagos 
commodity traders as highrolling fat cats with expensive german 
cars and luxurious homes on the lake michigan shore 
in an interview in his lawyers office pace said he owns a 1988 
chevy blazer and his wife cleo a realestate broker drives a 1988 
cadillac 
he said their cars and their threebedroom home in westmont a 
middleclass suburb not far from his bluecollar hometown of 
cicero are the only assets left to seize in the event of a 
racketeering conviction 
like many of the total 47 traders and a clerk who were indicted 
last year on commodity fraud charges in chicago pace contends he 
is a little fish caught in an indiscriminate fbi net 
it could have been anybody who was down there filling orders 
at that time he said 
paces defense is that he only did what everybody else was 
doing defense attorney steven rosenberg told the us district 
court jury in an opening statement sept 13 that pace and every 
other merc trader routinely violated exchange rules he said they 
changed or invented the prices at which customer orders were 
executed to repay other traders who absorbed their trading errors 
rosenberg said such rule violations did not constitute 
racketeering fraud or losses to customers he said exchange 
officials tolerated such activities although they deny it 
the son of a factory worker pace entered the risky world of 
commodities trading after a dissatisfying stint as a high school 
football and baseball coach during part of that time he was in 
the boxing ring 
i enjoyed it a lot but i just didnt see it financially 
said the ruggedly handsome pace who remains physically fit i 
was making 13000 or 14000 my first year i didnt know if i 
wanted to stay in coaching for 25 years to start making some decent 
money 
his wife was employed at that time by a commodities trading 
firm another trading company offered pace a job and he took it 
he began in 1982 as a runner carrying papers between the 
trading pits and his companys desk on the merc floor for 150 a 
week 
late in 1984 pace passed a series of exams and received his 
broker credentials he took ajob as an assistant to a more 
experienced broker who belonged to a broker association 
broker associations are groups of independent traders who fill 
customer orders for the major brokerage houses they pool a portion 
of their commissions to pay their shared expenses 
paces job was to stand next to his employer in the mercs swiss 
franc futures pit one of the pits that was later infiltrated by 
fbi agents and deal him the customer orders 
paces salary rose to 200 then 300 a week most of it went 
toward the exchange membership or seat that he leased through the 
broker association for about 800 a month the seat allowed him to 
trade in the pit 
i went through five to 10 grand of my own money to stay in 
business at that time because i wasnt making enough to pay the 
bills he recalled 
by 1988 pace said he was making enough money from commissions 
and personal trades to give up his salary he leased a more 
prestigious exchange seat for 3500 a month and moved from the 
swiss franc pit to the more active japanese yen pit 
fbi agent dietrich volk also was in the yen pit in 1988 posing 
as corrupt trader peter vogel while he secretly recorded 
conversations among traders inside and outside the pit 
pace was indicted in august 1989 along with 20 other traders 
from the yen pit representing about onefifth of the pits normal 
trader population seven of them have pleaded guilty to reduced 
charges 
pace said his income has fallen dramatically since his 
indictment while legal fees have consumed his life savings he has 
dropped back to the less expensive exchange membership and said his 
wife is seeking work with a steadier income than real estate sales 
pace said he and several other indicted yen traders have 
continued to fill customer orders despite the exchanges request 
that they refrain from doing so but his tradingthree new names were proposed 
tuesday for the 
union of soviet socialist republics including two that do away 
with the word soviet 
in a parliamentary debate on the union treaty that is being 
drawn up between the kremlin and the 15 soviet republics these 
names were proposed the union of sovereign socialist states the 
union of soviet sovereign republics and the union of euroasian 
republics 
rafik nishanov chairman of one of the supreme soviets two 
chambers and an ethnic uzbek revealed the names he said the 
proposed name change to the union of sovereign socialist states 
first reported sept 8 came from president mikhail s gorbachev 
the union of soviet sovereign republics came from a group of 
legislators from kazakhstan 
the union of euroasian republics was one entry in a contest 
organized by radical members of the parliament 
the word soviet is disliked by nationalist movements in some 
republics because they consider the soviets to be invaders who 
forced them to accept communist and russian domination 
nishanov has said a name change may be approved as part of the 
new union treaty which is expected to redefine the country as 
somewhere between a federation and an economic alliance action on 
the treaty is expected before the end of the year 
