a leading maker of computer data storage systems 
unveiled a new device tuesday it says represents the next 
generation of such technology 
the system from emc corp of hopkinton mass is designed to 
allow computers to get at information more quickly and reliably 
than traditional computer storage devices called hard disks 
the new storage system called redundant arrays of inexpensive 
disks or raid takes up less space than traditional hard disks 
while providing faster processing speeds and better reliability 
emc said at a news conference here the device costs 240000 to 
400000 
emc a major supplier of storage devices for international 
business machines corp computers said it was introducing its 
device at least 18 months ahead of similar systems planned by other 
manufacturers 
traditional mainframe computer storage devices consist of a 
single hard disk a 14inch magnetic device weighing about 144 
pounds the new emc technology combines several 5inch 10pound 
magnetic disks with a computerized controller that pulls data off 
the disks and another device that can temporarily store 
frequentlyused data 
